TY  - JOUR
AU  - van den Berg, Gerard J.
T1  - Nonstationarity in Job Search Theory
PY  - 1990
Y1  - 1990/04/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297381
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 57
IS  - 2
SP  - 255
EP  - 277
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - Generally, structural job search models are taken to be stationary. In this paper models are examined in which every exogenous variable can cause nonstationarity, for instance because its value is dependent on unemployment duration. A general differential equation that describes the evolution of the reservation wage over time is derived. As an empirical illustration a nonstationary structural model is estimated that focuses on the consequences of a downward shift in the level of benefits. It appears that the elasticity of duration with respect to the level of benefits after the shift is much larger than the elasticity with respect to the level before the shift.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297381
ER  - 



